Title: Spec Explorer — Product Walkthrough
Credit: SOMA team
Draft date: 2026-07-09

SETTINGS
format: 16:9
theme: soma-dark
default-transition: cut
captions: on
scene-gap: 0.5s

.BEAT 1 — The problem

MUSIC file:/Users/mikewolf/Projects/spec-explorer/film/assets/warm-bed.wav fade-in 2s duck: -14dB

CHROME
open http://localhost:4200/docstack.html
hold 4s

GEORGE
Every engineer knows this pile. A vacuum breaker manual, hundreds of pages, and a transformer standard written in the language of committees. The Siemens book is worse than dense — it's a scan. No selectable text, nothing you can search. You squint at a page and cross-reference a legend. Spec Explorer takes those two documents and makes them something you can actually use.

DISSOLVE TO:

.BEAT 2 — Ask the documents

CHROME
open http://localhost:4200
type "How do I manually charge the closing spring?" into css:#question
click css:#askBtn
wait for css:.a-body
hold 5s

SFX file:/Users/mikewolf/Projects/spec-explorer/film/assets/click.wav on css:#askBtn

GEORGE
So here's the first thing you can do — just ask it, in plain English. How do I manually charge the closing spring? Behind the scenes, that Siemens manual was a scan — no searchable text at all — so it was read by OCR, character by character, just to recover the words. Now the answer comes straight from that text, and only that text. No invented numbers. And it cites the page it came from, so you can go and check it yourself.

DISSOLVE TO:

.BEAT 3 — Figure 15, the mechanism

CHROME
open http://localhost:4200
click "Diagram explorer"
hold 1s
click css:.hotspot[data-id='62']
zoom 1.4 on css:.part-detail
hold 3s
zoom out

SFX file:/Users/mikewolf/Projects/spec-explorer/film/assets/click.wav on "Diagram explorer"

SFX file:/Users/mikewolf/Projects/spec-explorer/film/assets/click.wav on css:.hotspot[data-id='62']

GEORGE
Now, the diagram explorer. This is Figure 15 — the stored energy operating mechanism — a scanned photograph with three dozen numbered callouts. Every one of them is clickable. Click sixty-two, and the panel tells you: that's the closing spring, and what it does. The legend you used to hunt through is right there under your cursor.

DISSOLVE TO:

.BEAT 4 — Figure 17, the sequence

CHROME
open http://localhost:4200
click "Diagram explorer"
click "Figure 17"
hold 1s
scroll to css:.hotspot[data-id='T2']
click css:.hotspot[data-id='T2']
zoom 1.4 on css:.part-detail
hold 3s
zoom out

SFX file:/Users/mikewolf/Projects/spec-explorer/film/assets/click.wav on "Figure 17"

SFX file:/Users/mikewolf/Projects/spec-explorer/film/assets/click.wav on css:.hotspot[data-id='T2']

GEORGE
Back in the explorer, open Figure 17 — the operating sequence. How the breaker closes, and how it trips, drawn as a flowchart of cryptic device codes. Click a step — the shunt trip coil, fifty-two T — and it decodes the shorthand into plain English. Every box in the diagram, translated.

